FileTitle: A case study in dissemination: lessons learned from a pilot study involving the National Cancer Institute's Cancer Information Service.
DESCRIPTION: Evaluation area: Process (2005); Objectives: The Cancer Information Service Research Consortium (CISRC) was funded by the National Cancer Institute to disseminate as a pilot study a longitudinally tailored print intervention to promote the 5 A Day for Better Health program among callers to the National Cancer Institute's Cancer Information Service (CIS). FileTitle: Review of Wellcome Trust PhD Research Training: The Supervisor Perspective
DESCRIPTION: Evaluation area: Funding scheme (2000); Objectives: This study explored the opinions and experiences of the academic supervisors of Wellcome Trust-funded PhD students. It is the third in a series of studies examining Wellcome Trust PhD research training and follows on from 'Review of Wellcome Trust PhD Research Training: The Student Perspective' and 'Review of Wellcome Trust PhD Research Training: Career Paths of a 1988-1990 Prize Student Cohort', published in March 2000. Taken together, the reports constitute a comprehensive review of just over a decade of PhD student support by the Trust.; ; ; Published by: Wellcome Trust (NCRI); Methods: Survey, Case Study; Focus: Training;

FileTitle:
Strategic Analysis 2002
An overview of Cancer Research in the UK directly
funded by the NCRI Partner Organisations
DESCRIPTION: Evaluation area: Strategic analysis (2002); Objectives: Total spend on cancer research in the UK - industry spend alone in 2000 is thought to be in the region of 134 million per annum. Combining this figure with estimates from all the Government agencies and all the research charities, the total UK spend on cancer research can be estimated at between 450- 500 million per annum. NCRI brings together the 15 largest funders of cancer research from the Government and charity sectors with a collective spend of greater than 335 million per annum. Cancer research funding is made up of a number of different components. Direct support for research, is of most value for co-ordination and strategy setting. This Report presents an analysis of the direct spend component of cancer research (257 million per annum) funded by these fifteen leading UK cancer research organisations.; Published by: NCRI; Methods: Portfolio analysis; Focus: Gaps

FileTitle: A review of prostate cancer in the UK
DESCRIPTION: Evaluation area: Disease (2001); Objectives: Prostate cancer is the second most common cancer in men, being responsible for over 10,000 deaths each year in the UK. Most cases occur in older men but although there are fewer cases in the under fifties, the outcome for younger patients is less good. Early detection has been linked with improved outcome but uncertainties over diagnosis and best treatment, and concerns about the impact and reliability of screening, complicate the clinical picture. Against this background, the MRC conducted a review of UK prostate cancer activities on behalf of the Cancer Research Funders Forum; Site: Prostate; ; Published by: NCRI; Methods: Bibliometrics, Peer review, Benchmarking; Focus: Training, Collaboration, Infrastructure, Gaps;

Evaluation area: Research area/capacity (2003); Objectives: The review was designed to cover all

This new partnership, the National Cancer Research Institute (NCRI), has the role of maintaining strategic oversight of cancer research in the UK, the first ever database of cancer research in the UK; a identifying gaps and opportunities and co-ordinating fully comprehensive, up-to-date resource containing the funding activities of the Partner organisations.; ; ; Published by: NCRI; ; Focus: Performance against targets, ;

FileTitle:
Prevention and Risk
Research in the UK:
Report of the NCRI Strategic Planning
Group on Prevention and Risk
DESCRIPTION: Evaluation area: Research area/capacity (2004); Objectives: In October 2002, the NCRI published the first strategic analysis of the combined UK cancer research portfolio of the original 15 NCRI Partner organisations. The findings from the analysis highlighted that only 2% of the total cancer research funding by the NCRI Partners was spent on cancer prevention research. In response to this, the NCRI set up the Prevention and Risk Strategic Planning Group (SPG) to examine the status of research in cancer prevention and associated risk in the UK, in greater detail.; ; CSO3; Published by: NCRI; Methods: Bibliometrics, Peer review, Portfolio analysis, Survey; Focus: Public awareness, Collaboration, Gaps;

Research in the UK:

Palliative Care
DESCRIPTION: Evaluation area: Research area/capacity (2004); Objectives: The NCRI Strategic Analysis published in October 2002 revealed that research spend on supportive and palliative care was, at most, 11m per annum, which represented about 4.3% of direct research spend by NCRI Partners on cancer research. In response to this, the NCRI established a Strategic Planning Group (SPG) to examine the past and present state of UK research in this field and to make recommendations to the NCRI Board on strategic actions that could be undertaken to enhance research in this field.; ; CSO6; Published by: NCRI; Methods: Peer review, Portfolio analysis, Survey; Focus: Training, Collaboration, Infrastructure, Gaps;

FileTitle: Evaluation of clinical projects funded by the PHRC (Programme Hospitalier de Recherche Clinique) in 2003, 2004 and 2005
DESCRIPTION: Evaluation area: Cancer Plan (2008); Objectives: Looking at measures of success in clinical research programmes, therapeutic clinical trials, epidemiological & medical practice investigations and research into predictive or prognostic factors (2003, 2004) and biological therapies only (2005).  Studies were classed as Successful (study completed, or on track to complete), Intermediate (study ongoing, but with recruitment below the expected rates) and Failed.  Diverse reasons for failure were identified. FileTitle: Evaluation Extramural Grants Targeted Research on Cancer in the Poor and Medically Underserved Program
DESCRIPTION: Evaluation area: Funding scheme (2009); Objectives: One of the Societys overarching priority goals is the reduction of health disparities.  The Societys Extramural Grants Targeted Research on Cancer in the Poor and Medically Underserved Program was evaluated by the Societys RPAC. The program has been in existence for 10 years and 10% of the research grant budget was set aside to support health disparities reduction research. Analysis included applicant diversity, classification of targeted population (i.e. racial minority, sexual minority, low income populations, uninsured/underinsured, elderly, immigrants, etc), classification of study type (interventions, identification of predictors, dataset analysis, etc), classification of grants along the cancer continuum, and grantee achievements (i.e. career growth, awards and recognition, publications, subsequent funding, etc). ; Published by: ACS; Methods: Peer review, Portfolio analysis, Survey, Social analysis; ; KW: health disparities

FileTitle: Evaluation of Thirty Years Investment Recruiting and Training Scientists into Juvenile Diabetes Research (1974 - 2004)
DESCRIPTION: Evaluation area: Research area/capacity (2004); Objectives: The JDRF has utilized a variety of award mechanisms to support the recruitment and training of scientists and clinicians in diabetes research (Postdoctoral Fellowships, Advanced Postdoctoral Fellowships, and Career Development Awards). From 1974 through 2000, the JDRF awarded 794 PD and 144 CDA awards. In addition, in 2000 the JDRF established a new award aimed at senior postdoctoral fellows and awarded 22 APD in the first two years of the program. Of all former PD, APD, or CDA award recipients who responded to the survey, 84%, 96%, and 97% remain in diabetes related research. Overall, each of the training award programs established by the JDRF has resulted in recruitment and retention of scientists and clinicians into the field of diabetes research and clinical care.;  Published by: Juvenile Diabetes Research Foundation International; ; Focus: Training; KW: diabetes, research
